Q14_1: Assumed the fraction of the Cartogram the country I was measuring took up and used that to measure population, as the size of cartograms are directly proportional to population size
Q14_2: Depending on the clarity of the cartogram, I either guessed the grid squares which would fit in a country, or using the information in the legend created a scale factor to compare the two different dates. This method however involved a lot of guessing in terms of assumed size, however as mentioned before, the fact that the size of a cartogram is proportionate to the population, it made sense to assume fractions since majority of the population sizes were so large that a misestimation would not have made a huge difference. Especially when working with larger areas, a scale factor made more sense.
Q14_3: Much easier to predict, I would just count and estimate the grid lines, this became tiresome after a while however so I was less specific as time went on. When there was an a similar cartogram area, I would just count one set of grid lines, and multiply by the scale factor of the generally larger later date
Q14_4: Easily the fastest method, I found it beneficial to adjust the legends to the same size to be more accurate and adjust values accordingly based on the scale factor given. It was also much quicker to change to the largest size available, when maps were normally shaped and fit well in the square.

Q14_1: estimate the proportion that the region takes up then multiply that by the total
Q14_2: estimate how many boxes can fit inside the region then multiply that by the value of each box
Q14_3: count the number of boxes in the region then multiply by the value of each box
Q14_4: adjust the grid lines to make counting easier before counting and multiplying

Q14_1: Use estimation based on which one looks bigger in size
Q14_2: Take into consideration how much each grid represents, estimate based on the difference in values of the grids. Can estimate which is bigger but not the magnitude.
Q14_3: Count the number of squares that each area takes up and multiply it by the corresponding value of each square
Q14_4: Select the largest legend/grid lines and do the same as with unselectable legend/grid lines.

Q14_1: I had to estimate the proportion of the population occupied by each area in order to compare the population sizes for different years and estimate the population size of a region
Q14_2: Legends provided quantitative values that helped me to calculate the estimated population size based on a rough visual estimate of the proportion of areas on the cartogram
Q14_3: This helped me to more accurately and systematically calculate the area of each square in the grid to estimate the population size of a region, using the number of squares in the grid and the values provided in the legend
Q14_4: The strategy was the same as that of the legend and grid lines, however the calculation was made easier as I only needed to count less squares on the grid with larger legend sizes

Q14_1: I would guess the amount based on the total population, if the cartogram could be divided roughly into a 50-50 or 60-40 split.
Q14_2: I used a roughly similar strategy as when there were no legend or grid lines.
Q14_3: I would count the amount of grid squares occupied by a region, and then add 1 or 2 to it.
Q14_4: I would usually select the second scale of grid lines, as bigger squares tended to be easier for me to count.

Q14_1: estimating based on relative shape and size
Q14_2: looking at the size of the region, I estimated size based on the value given to me
Q14_4: i used the grid lines and legends that were easiest to count in order to best answer the question

Q14_1: comparing the areas of the different regions roughly in my head
Q14_2: approximating the number of squares within each area
Q14_4: aligning the populations for the square sizes and then counting

Q14_1: Roughly estimate proportions of the regions and deduce the number from the total number (but it only worked for maps with 2 or 3 regions)
Q14_2: Try to deduce from the ratio of the scales
Q14_3: Count number of squares and multiply by number in legend
Q14_4: The same as in non-selectable legend and grid-lines

Q14_1: Estimated the proportion of the area of the region with regards to the entire area and multiplied the population size by that proportion.
Q14_2: Compared the different values assigned to the boxes and then compared the size of the areas
Q14_3: counted the number of boxes that fit within the region and multiplied it by the value assigned to a box
Q14_4: Used the box size that fitted best in the region and counted the number of boxes, same as above

Q14_1: I tried to approximate a scale, but had to guess randomly or say that I didn't know the answer because it was next to impossible to be sure.
Q14_2: The legend was not very useful because I had to use a scale to approximate and the legend wasn't as helpful. I found myself just guessing.
Q14_3: The legend and grid lines were helpful. I used the grid boxes to approximate the number of people or whatever other parameter was listed.
Q14_4: This was the most useful setting. I used the largest possible grid lines to approximate the numbers of people between various graphs based on the number of filled squares. Also, I used the highlighting option to clearly compare between the locations listed.

Q14_1: I tried to imagine a grid line in my brain.
Q14_2: I try to compare the two regions first and then calculate roughly how many legend squares the area difference can fill in.
Q14_3: I try to use different sizes of the legend to come up with estimated number of squares, then multiply the number of squares to the number that the square represents.
Q14_4: I try to first select the grid lines and legend square that can fill in the maximum number of squares. Namely, I select the combination that gives me the easiest estimation. For example, when the squares are too small and it seems like I will save time if I switch to a bigger square, then I switch. Then I multiply the number of squares to the number each square represents.
